   "common": [
      {
         "text": "#### The formation of the archipelago\n\nGeologically speaking, the archipelago we know as Japan (Nippon koku or Nihon koku, 日本国) was formed by tectonic activity involving five different plates (Eurasian, Amur, Okhotsk, Pacific, and Philippine Sea), which resulted in four major islands (Hokkaido, Honshu, Shikoku, and Kyushu), as well as other smaller ones (<htcite0>).\n\nToday, we have a nation formed by an archipelago isolated from the continent, but this was not always the case. During the last ice age, there was a connection between some islands, such as Hokkaido, and the continent (<htcite1>).\n\n#### The migrations\n\nAll these natural factors created different migratory routes from the continent (**Figure 1**), which began to be used only “recently” (<htcite2>). This means that, although *Homo erectus* arrived in what is now China (Zhongguo, 中國) about one million years ago, regarding the occupation of Japan (Nippon koku or Nihon koku, 日本国), we only have evidence of our own species, *Homo sapiens* (<htcite3>; <htcite4>; <htcite5>; <htcite6>).\n\n#### First populations\n\nDespite the few fossils and, as a consequence, the scarce genetic information from before the Jomon period (縄文), that is, in the Paleolithic, it is not non-existent. For this reason, we take the liberty of presenting some information from the work of Yuichi Nakazawa.\n\nSince <htdate0>, several Paleolithic sites have been discovered in Japan. Currently, the oldest sites date between <htdate1> and <htdate2>. Another fact observed at these sites is that there is a greater abundance in the southern region of Japan (Nippon koku or Nihon koku, 日本国), that is, possibly originating from the Korean Peninsula or China (Zhongguo, 中國) (<htcite7>).",
         "source": [
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "f86e0289-d28d-4d07-8ba2-f18c84df98b4",
               "text": "Nakazawa, Y.",
